ning the inherited methods, is also returning the inherited methods that **are overwritten and use generics**. To solve this I suggest using the method below:\r\n\r\n```java\r\npublic class ReflectionUtils {\r\n    public static List<Method> getDeclaredMethods(Class clazz) {\r\n        // @formatter:off\r\n        return Arrays\r\n                .stream(clazz.getDeclaredMethods())\r\n                .filter(method -> !method.isBridge())\r\n                .collect(Collectors.toList());\r\n        // @formatter:on\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nI noticed this because I have a Controller that inherits from a generic Controller (see below) ...\r\n\r\n```java\r\npublic abstract class CrudControllerAbstract<ID extends Serializable> {\r\n    protected void delete(ID id) {\r\n    \t// ...\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\npublic class LoggerEntityController extends CrudControllerAbstract<Long> {\r\n    @GET(\"/logger/delete/{id}\")\r\n    public void delete(@Param(\"id\") Long id) {\r\n        super.delete(id);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n... and Pippo has created two routes for the same method. This problem - of creating two routes for the same method - can be solved with the code I suggest above, but also has a connection with a ``strange/different/bizarre`` behavior that I say below in [2].\r\n\r\n**[2]**\r\nI saw a different behavior with the same (same same!) JVM version in ``Fedora 25`` and ``RHEL 7`` in the method ``Method.getAnnotations()`` in\r\nhttps://github.com/decebals/pippo/blob/release-1.5.0/pippo-controller-parent/pippo-controller/src/main/java/ro/pippo/controller/ControllerRegistry.java#L275\r\n\r\nIn the loop in ``ControllerRegistry.java#L274``, as I said in [1], the methods ``LoggerEntityController.delete(java.lang.Long)`` and ``LoggerEntityController.delete(java.io.Serializable)`` are iterated. For the method ``LoggerEntityController.delete(java.lang.Long)`` the ``method.getAnnotations()`` returns the `@GET` annotation and all ok here, but for the method ``LoggerEntityController.delete(java.io.Serializable)`` the ``method.getAnnotations()`` has different results in my ``Fedora 25`` and ``RHEL 7``. In ``Fedora 25`` it does not return any annotations and everything is ok here, but in ``RHEL 7`` it returns the `@GET` annotation and here we have a problem since this method is not annotated with `@GET`. In ``RHEL 7``, since both methods are erroneously found to have the `@GET` annotation, then two routes are added for the same method (ControllerRegistry.java#L277: httpMethodAnnotationClasses.contains(annotationClass) is true).\r\n\r\n```\r\njava -version\r\njava version \"1.8.0_121\"\r\nJava(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.8.0_121-b31)\r\nJava HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 25.121-b31, mixed mode)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**[3]**\r\nA pull request with the ReflectionUtils class [1] is valid and use it on the ControllerRegistry.java#L275 ?\r\n\r\nPS: I find it a bit complicated to explain. If I can clarify more, let me know.","score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pippo-java/pippo/issues/399","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pippo-java/pippo","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pippo-java/pippo/issues/399/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pippo-java/pippo/issues/399/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pippo-java/pippo/issues/399/events","html_url":"https://github.com/pippo-java/pippo/issues/399","id":261854538,"number":399,"title":"[Question] Access controller method from RouteContext","user":{"login":"codematix","id":8013222,"avatar_url":"https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/8013222?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/codematix","html_url":"https://github.com/codematix","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/codematix/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/codematix/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/codematix/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/codematix/starr